<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>RECONDITIONING ROTORS - INSPECTION - HEAT-SPOTTED ROTORS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
        <title>HEAT-SPOTTED ROTORS</title>
        <para>This condition indicates that the rotor has been subjected to extremely high temperatures that have caused
            a structural change in the rotor material, making it more susceptible to cracking (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401818">Figure 18
                <xref refid="f0401818"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ).
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401818" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401818" filename="../figg04/G0401818.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 18. Heated-Spotted Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>Rotors should be turned to restore their parallelism by removing the hard raised areas. If resurfacing
            will not remove the spots--or if resurfacing reduces the rotor thickness below the minimum recommended
            thickness stamped on the O.D. of the rotor (
            <hotlnk document="s04018w_4.xml" xrefid="f0401810">Figure 10
                <xref refid="f0401810"/>
            </hotlnk>
            )--the rotor must be replaced.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
